value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: reduced rubredoxin + NAD+ = oxidized rubredoxin + NADH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction: reduced rubredoxin + NAD(P)+ = oxidized rubredoxin + NAD(P)H + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction: reduced rubredoxin + NADP+ = oxidized rubredoxin + NADPH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction: NADPH + H+ + 2 ferricytochrome c2 = NADP+ + 2 ferrocytochrome c2.

Catalysis of the transfer of electrons between pyridine nucleotides (obligatory two-electron carriers) and hemes or (2Fe-2S) centers (obligatory one-electron carriers) in respiration, photosynthesis, and many oxygenase systems.
Catalysis of the reaction: methane + NAD(P)H + H+ + O2 = methanol + NAD(P)+ + H2O.
A protein complex that possesses methane monooxygenase activity; dimeric and trimeric complexes have been characterized.
Combining with epinephrine or norepinephrine to initiate a change in cell activity via activation of a G protein, with pharmacological characteristics of beta3-adrenergic receptors.
Combining with gastrin and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with secretin to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with the corticotrophin-releasing factor family of ligands, including the urocortins, to initiate a change in cell activity.
A G protein-coupled receptor activity that is activated by cleavage by thrombin, which exposes a tethered ligand corresponding to the new N-terminus, which binds to the receptor and activates it.
Binds to and stops, prevents or reduces the activity of alpha-amylase.
Catalysis of the reversible transfer of an amidino group to an acceptor.
Catalysis of the reaction: L-arginine + glycine = L-ornithine + guanidinoacetate.
Catalysis of the reaction: 1-amino-1-deoxy-scyllo-inositol 4-phosphate + L-arginine = 1-guanidino-1-deoxy-scyllo-inositol 4-phosphate + L-ornithine.
The process in which a DNA segment is incorporated into another, usually larger, DNA molecule such as a chromosome.

label.value: high-affinity copper ion transmembrane transporter activity

value.value: Enables the transfer of a copper ions (Cu2+) from one side of a membrane to the other. In high-affinity transport the transporter is able to bind the solute even if it is only present at very low concentrations.

label.value: low-affinity ferric iron ion transmembrane transporter activity

value.value: Enables the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction: Fe2+(out) = Fe2+(in). In low-affinity transport the transporter is able to bind the solute only if it is present at very high concentrations.
Enables the transfer of ferric iron (Fe(III) or Fe3+) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.

definition.value: Ferric iron is rarely transported in the free form. Some bacteria have a system in which an outer membrane protein takes iron away from host ferritin or lactoferrin and transport it to a Fe3+ binding protein in the periplasm. The periplasmic protein then delivers the Fe3+ to a transport system located in the cytoplasmic membrane. Consider also GO:0015343 siderophore transmembrane transporter activity.

label.value: high-affinity ferric iron transmembrane transporter activity

value.value: Enables the transfer of ferric iron (Fe(III) or Fe3+) ions from one side of a membrane to the other. In high-affinity transport the transporter is able to bind the solute even if it is only present at very low concentrations.
Enables the transfer of ferrous iron (Fe(II) or Fe2+) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.

Enables the transfer of magnesium (Mg) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Enables the transfer of mercury (Hg2+) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Enables the transfer of molybdate (MoO4 2-) ions from one side of a membrane to the other. Molybdate is the bivalent anion derived from molybdic acid.
Enables the transfer of nickel (Ni) cations from one side of a membrane to the other.
Enables the transfer of vanadium (V) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Enables the transfer of organic cations from one side of a membrane to the other. Organic cations are atoms or small molecules with a positive charge that contain carbon in covalent linkage.

Enables the transfer of inorganic anions from one side of a membrane to the other. Inorganic anions are atoms or small molecules with a negative charge which do not contain carbon in covalent linkage.
Enables the transfer of antimonite from one side of a membrane to the other.
Enables the transfer of arsenite from one side of a membrane to the other.
Enables the transfer of bicarbonate from one side of a membrane to the other. Bicarbonate is the hydrogencarbonate ion, HCO3-.
Enables the transfer of chlorate, ClO3-, from one side of a membrane to the other.
Enables the transfer of chloride ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Enables the transfer of chromate from one side of a membrane to the other. Chromate is the anion of chromic acid, H2CrO4 (aq) or CrO3.
Enables the transfer of cyanate, NCO-, the anion of cyanic acid, from one side of a membrane to the other.
Enables the transfer of iodide ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Enables the transfer of nitrate ions (NO3-) from one side of a membrane to the other.
Enables the transfer of nitrite (NO2-) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.

Enables the transfer of silicates from one side of a membrane to the other. Silicates are the salts of silicic acids, and are usually composed of silicon and oxygen (Si[x]O[y]), one or more metals, and possibly hydrogen. Types of silicate include unisilicates, metasilicates and hydrous silicates.
